    "Mitchell G. Reddish, Nijay K. Gupta": "Words of Praise\u20142:2-3, 6\n3. Words of Praise\u20142:9\n3. Words of Praise\u20142:13\n3. Words of Praise\u20142:19\n3. Words of Praise\u20143:4\n3. The majority of manuscripts end the verse with \u201camen.\u201d Several manuscripts, including an early,\nimportant one, do not have \u201camen.\u201d\n433",
    "E.W. Bullinger": "The Acts and earlier Pauline Epistles; the King and Kingdom re-offered (iii. 19-21);\nand rejected, by the Dispersion in Rome (Acts xxviii. 25, 26).",
    "John Trapp": "And hast borne ] Bear the false apostles thou couldst not; but hast borne much from them. Morientium nempe ferarum violentiores sunt morsus. Beasts bite hardest when to bite their last.\nVer.\n3. For his principality; the lion is the king of beasts.\n3. Lovingness, #2Sa 1:26 . Clothed with the sun ] With Christ\u2019s own comeliness, #Eze 16:14 . She is also conspicuous, #Mt 5:14 , and scorched with persecution, #So 1:6 . All which notwithstanding she is comely. Uxor fulget radiis mariti, saith the Civilian. And the moon under her feet ] She treads upon the world\u2019s trash, bears patiently all changes and chances; and though the curs of the world bark at her, she shines still: \u201c En peragit cursus surda Diana suas. \u201d A crown of twelve stars ] A crown in token of victory. Twelve stars ] Those white horses, #Re 6:2 , the twelve apostles and their successors, in and by whom mystical Christ goeth forth conquering and to conquer.\nVer.\n3. Another wonder in heaven ] That is, in the Church, which is called heaven; for,\n3. In the faith of his people;\n3. Neuters. And the cities of the nations ] That came to aid Antichrist. And great Babylon ] Augustine and other ancients do call Rome the Western Babylon; and do so compare them, as that Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` was born in the flourish of the first Babylon, Christ of the second. The `[object_Tabernacle_Heb_9]` Jesuits here, though they grant Rome to be Babylon, yet they would have it to be Rome heathen under the emperors, and not Rome Christian under the popes. But it must be Rome Christian, as it appears by a double departure:\n3. And hast borne] Bear the false apostles thou couldst not; but hast borne much from them. Morientium nempe ferarum violentiores sunt morsus. Beasts bite hardest when to bite their last.\nVer.\n3. Ver.\n3. For his principality; the lion is the king of beasts.\n3. Which are the prayers of saints] That is, their own prayers and [v_Rev_5_9] praises, recorded #Re 5:\n3. They began the song, and so conclude it, as having far greater benefit by Christ than all other creatures, and God expects a proportion, that our returns be somewhat answerable to our receipts. (Sarson.) The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` saints upon earth sing a new (that is, an [v_Rev_5_9] excellent) song in the honour of Christ, #Re 5:9,\n3. Lovingness, #2Sa 1:26. [v_Ezk_16_14] Clothed with the sun] With Christ\u2019s own comeliness, #Eze 16:\n3. Another wonder in heaven] That is, in the Church, which [v_Jhn_1_13] is called heaven; for,\n3. Its conversation in heaven, #Php 3:20\n3. But here is the comfort, Christ appears in heaven for his (as a lawyer appears for his client), to nonsuit all the [v_Heb_9_24] devil\u2019s accusations, #Heb 9:\n3. In the faith of his people;\n3. Neuters. And the cities of the nations] That came to aid Antichrist. And great Babylon] Augustine and other ancients do call Rome the Western Babylon; and do so compare them, as that Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` was born in the flourish of the first Babylon, Christ of the second. The Jesuits here, though they grant Rome to be Babylon, yet they would have it to be Rome heathen under the emperors, and not Rome Christian under the popes. But it must be Rome Christian, as it appears by a double departure:"
