    "Mitchell G. Reddish, Nijay K. Gupta": "Words of Criticism\u20142:4\n4. Words of Criticism\u2014(Missing)\n4. Words of Criticism\u20142:14-15\n4. Words of Criticism\u20142:20-23\n4. Words of Criticism\u20143:1c",
    "E.W. Bullinger": "The Later Pauline Epistles. The Kingdom in abeyance. The King made Head over all\nthings to the Church.",
    "John Trapp": "Thou hast left thy first love ] Those first ripe fruits that Christ\u2019s soul desireth, #Mic 7:1 , that kindness of youth, that spousal love, that God so well remembereth, #Jer 2:2 . This Ephesus had left, and so became Aphesis, remiss and reckless, possessed with a spirit of sloth and indevotion. And surely he is a rare and happy man that can say in a spiritual sense (as it was said of Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]`), that after long profession of zeal, his sight is not waxed dim, his holy heat not abated, that runs not retrograde, as did Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]`, Asa, others, with whom the end was worse than the beginning.\nVer.\n4. For his vigilancy; the lion sleepeth with open eyes. (Gerhard.) The Root of David `[char_David_Rut_4]` ] So the prophets. \"They have Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` and the prophets,\" saith Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]`, #Lu 16:29 \"To the law and to the testimony,\" #Isa 8:20 . If any speak not according to this word, it is because there is no light in them, nor to be gotten from them. Hath prevailed ] Gr . \u03b5\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03b7\u03c3\u03b5\u03bd, hath overcome, or surpassed, sc. all creatures in worth, to do this great work.\nVer.\n4. And his tail drew ] A monstrous tail for length and strength. One interprets it as his dog-like flattering tail, whence the proverb grew, Cauda blandiri, to be flattered by a tail, \u03ba\u03b5\u03c1\u03ba\u03c9 \u03c3\u03b1\u03b9\u03bd\u03b5\u03b9\u03bd. Julian the Apostate drew many from the faith by flatteries and fair promises. Luther was offered a cardinalship to be quiet. (Bp Carlton\u2019s Tha nkf. Remem.) The pope offered Queen Elizabeth to confirm the English Liturgy by his authority, granting also the use of the sacraments under both kinds, so that she would join herself to the Roman Church. And how the pope clawed our king when he was in Spain, A. D. 1623, is better known than that I need here to relate. (Jac. Revius, vit. Pontif.) And the dragon stood before the woman ] This implieth,\n4. Thou hast left thy first love] Those first ripe fruits that [v_Mic_7_1] Christ\u2019s soul desireth, #Mic 7:1, that kindness of youth, that [v_Jer_2_2] spousal love, that God so well remembereth, #Jer 2:\n4. Ver.\n4. God hath his season, his harvest for judgment, #Mt 13:\n4. For his vigilancy; the lion sleepeth with open eyes. (Gerhard.) The Root of David `[char_David_Rut_4]`] So the prophets. \"They have Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` and the [v_Luk_16_29] prophets,\" saith Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]`, #Lu 16:29 \"To the law and to the [v_Isa_8_20] testimony,\" #Isa 8:\n4. Its dependence upon heaven, #Jas 1:\n4. And his tail drew] A monstrous tail for length and strength. One interprets it as his dog-like flattering tail, whence the proverb grew, Cauda blandiri, to be flattered by a tail, \u03ba\u03b5\u03c1\u03ba\u03c9 \u03c3\u03b1\u03b9\u03bd\u03b5\u03b9\u03bd. Julian the Apostate drew many from the faith by flatteries and fair promises. Luther was offered a cardinalship to be quiet. (Bp Carlton\u2019s Thankf. Remem.) The pope offered Queen Elizabeth to confirm the English Liturgy by his authority, granting also the use of the sacraments under both kinds, so that she would join herself to the Roman Church. And how the pope clawed our king when he was in Spain, A. D. 1623, is better known than that I need here to relate. (Jac. Revius, vit. Pontif.) And the dragon stood before the woman] This implieth,\n4. By this great eagle, [v_Ezk_17_3] [v_Ezk_17_4] [v_Ezk_17_5] [v_Ezk_17_6] [v_Ezk_17_7] some mighty personage seems to be designed, #Eze 17:3-"
